**Abstract:**
A concise essay titled "From the XIth to the XIIth century," tracing the transformation of the relationship between philosophy and theology from the 11th to 13th centuries. Before the 11th century, the Bible was the sole authoritative text with no distinction between scientific and religious reading. In the 11th century, logic began to be applied to the Bible with the problem of universals. In the 12th century, Lombard's Sententiae created a second theological text, and the translation of Aristotle's corpus introduced an alternative worldview and evidentialist discourse. By the 13th century, philosophy became autonomous though subordinate, theology became speculative rather than storica, and biblical reading split between devotional (personal meditation, preaching) and scientific (theoretical, assent-based).

**AI Recommendation:** Valuable historical overview summarizing the epistemological rupture thesis; provides timeline of the transformation described in the larger Chantilly project.

